ğŸ” AD Credential Validator

A lightweight Python tool for validating Active Directory username + password pairs using NTLM authentication.
Useful for security teams, SOC pipelines, and credential verification workflows.

ğŸš€ Features

Validates NTLM authentication directly against an Active Directory domain controller

Accepts input in either email format (user@example.com) or DOMAIN\username`

No service account needed â€” authentication is attempted using the provided credentials

Simple CLI interface for manual testing

Can be integrated into automation tools (SOAR, n8n, playbooks, pipelines)

ğŸ“¦ Installation
git clone https://github.com/maryamoah/validator.git
cd validator
pip install -r requirements.txt

ğŸ”§ Usage
python validate_ad_creds.py <email_or_username> <password>


Examples:

python validate_ad_creds.py user@example.com "SomePassword123"
python validate_ad_creds.py DOMAIN\\username "P@ssw0rd!"

ğŸ“ Output Examples

Valid credentials:

[INFO] Validating: user@example.com
[RESULT] âœ… VALID CREDS (User + Password are correct)


Invalid credentials:

[INFO] Validating: user@example.com
[RESULT] âŒ INVALID (User not found OR password incorrect)

âš™ï¸ Configuration

Update the domain controller (DC) address:

AD_SERVER = "your.domain.controller"


This must point to a reachable AD server that supports NTLM authentication.

ğŸ”’ Security Notes

Credentials are used only for real-time authentication and never stored

No logs are written to disk unless you enable your own logging

NTLM authentication requires direct network access to the domain controller

Only validates username + password, does not modify or enumerate users

ğŸ§© Limitations

Requires network connectivity to your AD domain controller

NTLM authentication must be enabled on the server

Anonymous LDAP queries may not work depending on AD security configuration

